<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is Base64 encoding?", answer: "Base64 encoding converts binary data into a text format using 64 ASCII characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /). It is commonly used to embed binary data in text-based formats like JSON, XML, HTML, and email. Base64 increases data size by approximately 33% but ensures the data can be safely transmitted through text-only channels." },
  { question: "What is URL encoding?", answer: "URL encoding (also called percent-encoding) replaces unsafe characters in URLs with a percent sign followed by two hexadecimal digits. For example, a space becomes %20, an ampersand becomes %26, and a question mark becomes %3F. This ensures special characters do not break URL parsing or create ambiguity in query parameters." },
  { question: "What are HTML entities?", answer: "HTML entities are special sequences that represent characters in HTML that would otherwise be interpreted as markup. The ampersand becomes &amp;, less-than becomes &lt;, greater-than becomes &gt;, and double quotes become &quot;. Using HTML entities prevents cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks and ensures text displays correctly in web pages." },
  { question: "When should I use Base64 encoding?", answer: "Use Base64 encoding when embedding images or files in HTML/CSS, sending binary data in JSON APIs, encoding email attachments (MIME), storing binary data in text databases, and encoding authentication credentials in HTTP headers (Basic auth). Do not use Base64 for encryption as it is trivially reversible." },
  { question: "Is encoding the same as encryption?", answer: "No. Encoding transforms data into a different format for safe transmission or display but provides no security. Anyone can decode Base64, URL encoding, or HTML entities. Encryption transforms data to make it unreadable without a secret key. Use encoding for data format compatibility and encryption for data security." }
]) %>

